Sentencas: A solid oxide fuel cell (SOFC) test unit was constructed with yttria-stabilized zirconia (YSZ) as the solid electrolyte, Ni-YSZ as the anode and Pt as the cathode.
Titulo: Effect of operating conditions on the electrochemical behavior of hydrogen-fed solid oxide fuel cells

Sentencas: The SOFC unit was tested by varying hydrogen supply time, voltage, and temperature at 700-900 degrees C.
Titulo: Effect of operating conditions on the electrochemical behavior of hydrogen-fed solid oxide fuel cells

Sentencas: The phenomena of electrochemical promotion of bulk lattice-oxygen extraction and fuel-free current have been observed.
Titulo: Effect of operating conditions on the electrochemical behavior of hydrogen-fed solid oxide fuel cells

Sentencas: The amount of lattice oxygen additionally extracted by electrochemical promotion is limited.
Titulo: Effect of operating conditions on the electrochemical behavior of hydrogen-fed solid oxide fuel cells

Sentencas: This limitation is more pronounced as the operating temperature increases.
Titulo: Effect of operating conditions on the electrochemical behavior of hydrogen-fed solid oxide fuel cells

Sentencas: The interstitial hydrogen species are formed as either the interstitial hydrogen atoms in the bulk of Ni electrode or the interstitial protons in the bulk of YSZ.
Titulo: Effect of operating conditions on the electrochemical behavior of hydrogen-fed solid oxide fuel cells

Sentencas: The amount of the interstitial hydrogen species is also limited.
Titulo: Effect of operating conditions on the electrochemical behavior of hydrogen-fed solid oxide fuel cells

Sentencas: Oxygen transport in YSZ to the YSZ-Ni interface is rate limiting for H2O formation over the anode.
Titulo: Effect of operating conditions on the electrochemical behavior of hydrogen-fed solid oxide fuel cells

Sentencas: These new characteristics on the electrochemical behavior can optimize the operating conditions and the designing features of hydrogen-fed SOFCs.
Titulo: Effect of operating conditions on the electrochemical behavior of hydrogen-fed solid oxide fuel cells
